d work fine even while ES is running. The `reload_secure_settings` endpoint requires authentication, which complicates the postStart hook and risks failing the container startup. For now, I just need the Secret to exist and the keystore entries populated for snapshots to work. I'm going to take a simpler approach: keep the init container but write to a temporary directory instead, and avoid mounting the keystore as a subPath in the main container.\n\nThe real question is whether Kubernetes sets up the subPath bind mount before the init container runs. Let me test using a memory-backed emptyDir for the keystore volume to see if that changes how the bind mount behaves.\n\nActually, I should just try a completely different approach that sidesteps this whole problem. I'll revert the StatefulSet to remove the init container and keystore volume setup, then add the `es-secure-settings` Secret as a volume mounted in the main container at a readable path. Instead of using an init container, I'll add a postStart lifecycle hook that runs the keystore add command directly in the main container's context, then reload the secure settings once the pods are ready.\n\nThe tricky part is patching arrays in JSON to remove elements—I need to know the exact indices. Let me check the current StatefulSet state to figure out what's actually there now, since elasticsearch-2 is on the new broken spec while the other pods are still running the old one.\n\nActually, I should design the correct StatefulSet in one shot so the rolling restart only happens once. I need to include all the original volumes plus the es-secure-settings Secret volume and a memory-backed keystore volume, then modify the setup-keystore init container to use the temporary keystore location and set the proper environment variables.\n\nBut I'm realizing the core issue: how do I get the keystore from the init container's emptyDir into the main container's config directory? I'm also questioning whether subPath mounts in the init container are causing the EBUSY error. Looking at how Kubernetes handles this, init containers and main containers have separate mount namespaces, so the subPath bind mount shouldn't affect the init container at all. The EBUSY error when trying to rename the keystore file must be coming from something else.\n\nWhat if the keystore file itself is locked by another process? The fix-perms init container only touches the data directory, not config, so that's not the culprit. Or maybe the elasticsearch-keystore commands are conflicting with each other since they're running sequentially in the same script with some kind of file locking issue.\n\nLooking at the init container command more closely, I'm piping the S3 access and secret keys into separate add commands after the initial create, which should work fine sequentially. But I'm wondering if the `create -s` command is actually succeeding or if it's silently failing because the keystore already exists in ES 8.x.\n\nThe Docker image might ship with a pre-existing keystore at the default location, and if that's the case, the create command with the silent flag could be skipping the overwrite. Then when the add commands try to update this existing keystore, the rename operation during the save might fail if there's a permissions issue or the file is locked. Actually, let me take a step back and debug this empirically. I'll check the init container logs to see what's actually failing, then try running the keystore commands directly on the main container once it's running. My plan is to fix the failed pod, wait for everything to stabilize, then exec into each pod to manually add the keystore settings and reload the secure settings endpoint, followed by registering the repository and snapshot.\n\nFor the permanent fix in the StatefulSet, I'll remove the problematic init container and keystore volume mount, keeping just the volume itself mounted in the main container so I can use postStart or exec commands later.","signat