arch.yml, log4j2.properties, and any other defaults from the image into the emptyDir first, then add the keystore.\n\nActually, the cleaner approach is to mount the keystore-vol at a different path in the main container and use `ES_PATH_CONF` environment variable to tell Elasticsearch where to find its config, so it picks up the keystore from there while still using the subPath mount for elasticsearch.yml. .conf`, so they're resolved relative to the config path. That means if I change `ES_PATH_CONF`, I need to move the users and roles files there too. My revised approach is to use an init container that assembles all the config files—elasticsearch.yml, users, users_roles, and roles.yml—into an emptyDir, then creates the keystore there, while the main container keeps the TLS certs mounted separately since they use absolute paths. Setting up the init container with volume mounts...\n\nCopying config files to the combined directory and creating the keystore with the new path...\n\nFor the main container, I need to set the `ES_PATH_CONF` environment variable to point to the combined config directory, mount the `config-combined` emptyDir there, and remove the individual subPath mounts since they're now handled by the init container. The certificate mount stays as-is since it uses an absolute path unaffected by the config path variable. This approach avoids the file rename issue by consolidating everything upfront in the init container. Actually, I'm overcomplicating this. Let me look at the error again—the rename is failing on the overlay filesystem. What if the real issue is that `elasticsearch-keystore create -s` either fails silently or doesn't run due to the command chain, and then `elasticsearch-keystore add --stdin` tries to write to a keystore that doesn't exist, creating a `.tmp` file but failing when it can't rename over a non-existent file? Though that doesn't quite make sense either since renaming to a non-existent file should work. Or maybe `elasticsearch-key