eystore volume at `/es-config` without subPath, set `ES_PATH_CONF=/es-config`, and remove the individual subPath mounts for config and file-realm since they'll all be in the emptyDir. The init container needs to copy the elasticsearch.yml, users, users_roles, and roles.yml files into the keystore volume before creating the keystore. The certificate paths in elasticsearch.yml use absolute paths so they don't depend on `ES_PATH_CONF`, and the certs volume mounted at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs` will work fine as-is. I need to add the `ES_PATH_CONF=/es-config` environment variable to the main container. The elasticsearch.yml uses absolute paths for the certificate locations, so those will work fine regardless of the config path. Since ES has defaults for other config files like log4j2.properties, missing files won't cause issues—it'll just use the built-in defaults.\n\nBut wait, I'm realizing the official ES Docker image already sets `ES_PATH_CONF` to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config` by default. If I override it to `/es-config`, ES will stop looking in the original config directory entirely, which means it won't pick up jvm.options files, log4j2.properties, or security policy files from there. That could break things.\n\nA better approach would be to have the init container copy all the config files from the image's original config directory into the emptyDir first, then add the keystore to it. That way the main container can use `ES_PATH_CONF=/es-config` and still have access to everything it needs.\n\nThe init container can do this because it uses the same image as the main container, so it has access to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/`. It would copy everything there to the emptyDir, then overlay the configmap content and file-realm files on top.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a potential issue: copying recursively from the image's config directory might fail due to permissions, or it could accidentally override the configmap values if the order isn't right.\n\nThe cleaner approach is to mount the configmap directly at the same path in both the init container and main container, then have the init container only handle the keystore setup. That way the configmap's elasticsearch.yml is already in place without needing to copy it. I'm realizing there's a mismatch: the certs directory is mounted in the main container but not in the init container, so when I copy the config to `/es-config/`, the certs won't be included. Since Elasticsearch would look for certs relative to `ES_PATH_CONF=/es-config`, this creates a problem where it can't find the certificate files. So if `ES_PATH_CONF=/es-config`, Elasticsearch reads the config from `/es-config/elasticsearch.yml`, which specifies cert paths as absolute paths pointing to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs`. Since those certs are mounted there in the main container, that resolves correctly. But I need to verify whether Elasticsearch also looks for `jvm.options`, `log4j2.properties`, and other config files relative to `ES_PATH_CONF`...\n\nActually, it does — Elasticsearch expects all its config files in that directory. The init container can copy everything from `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/` into the emptyDir at `/es-config/`, which gives us all the JVM options and logging configuration we need. The only issue is permissions: the init container runs as the elasticsearch user (uid 1000), but the emptyDir starts owned by root, so I need to either run the init container as root to set proper permissions, or find another way to handle the ownership.\n\nLet me revise the StatefulSet patch to replace the broken setup-keystore container with a new setup-config container that copies the Elasticsearch config files and handles permissions correctly.\n\nI need to verify the init container copies all necessary files from the default config directory to the emptyDir volume, then sets the ES_PATH_CONF environment variable to point there instead of using individual subPath mounts.